{"id":"1808.03893","submitter":"Shuya Chiba","authors":"Shuya Chiba, Suyun Jiang, Jin Yan","title":"Partitioning a graph into cycles with a specified number of chords","comments":"13 pages, 2 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  For a graph $G$, let $\\sigma_{2}(G)$ be the minimum degree sum of two\nnon-adjacent vertices in $G$. A chord of a cycle in a graph $G$ is an edge of\n$G$ joining two non-consecutive vertices of the cycle. In this paper, we prove\nthe following result, which is an extension of a result of Brandt et al. (J.\nGraph Theory 24 (1997) 165-173) for large graphs: For positive integers $k$ and\n$c$, there exists an integer $f(k,c)$ such that, if $G$ is a graph of order $n\n\\ge f(k, c)$ and $\\sigma_{2}(G) \\ge n$, then $G$ can be partitioned into $k$\nvertex-disjoint cycles, each of which has at least $c$ chords.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 12 Aug 2018 05:38:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-08-14"}
